      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"absurdity\" you describe is actually the existence of the great philosopher Albert Camus, who argued we must imagine our own absurdity as rebellious, not as despairing. You don't need a grand cosmic purpose to find value in the tangible, rhythmic pain of waking your body in the morning or the color of the sunset. Sometimes, the only act of resistance is to refuse to let the universe's coldness steal the warmth of your specific, unscripted life right now.",
      "source": "target",
